We can use polynomial division to find the remainder. Long division is cumbersome, so we will use synthetic division instead (which is basically a shortcut to long division). 

First, we write $-2$ outside of the division symbol and list the coefficients of the polynomial inside the division symbol in descending order of degree. We also write $-2$ to the side.

\begin{array}{c|ccccc}
-2 & 5 & 0 & 9 & 0 & \cdots \\
\hline
& & & & & \\
\end{array}

Now we bring down the first coefficient, which is $5.$

\begin{array}{c|ccccc}
-2 & 5 & 0 & 9 & 0 & \cdots \\
\hline
& & & & & \\
\cline{2-6}
& & 5 & & & \\
\end{array}

Next, we multiply the number $-2$ by the previous result, which is $5,$ and write the product underneath the next coefficient, which is $0.$ We add these numbers to get $-10.$ We repeat this process until we get the last term of the polynomial.

\begin{array}{c|ccccc}
-2 & 5 & 0 & 9 & 0 & \cdots \\
\hline
& & -10 & 20 & -58 & \cdots \\
\cline{2-6}
& & 5 & 20 & -58 & \cdots \\
\end{array}

The last number we get is the remainder. So when $(5x + 9)^{611} + (x + 5)^{11} + (x - 1)^{11} + 3x^2 + 1$ is divided by $x + 2,$ the remainder is $-58x + 96.$ Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{-58x + 96}.$

The equation of the circle is $x^2 + y^2 = 1994^2.$ Since the point $(2 \cdot 1994, 2 \cdot 1994)$ lies on the line connecting the origin with the point $(1994,1994),$ the center of the circle, the line connecting these two points is a tangent to the circle.

[asy]
unitsize(0.0025 inch);
pair O, P, Q;
O = (0,0);
P = (1994,1994);
Q = reflect(O,P)*(2*P);
draw(Circle(O,1994));
draw(P--Q--O);
draw(rightanglemark(O,Q,P,400));
draw(Q--(Q.x,-Q.y));
label("$(1994,1994)$", P, N);
label("$(2 \cdot 1994, 2 \cdot 1994)$", Q, NE);
label("$O$", (2000,0), SE);
label("$a$", midpoint(P--Q), N);
